	"Description": "The Family Enrichment Center, Inc. (FEC) is a private, faith-based, not-for-profit child-placing agency founded by the College Hill Church of God in Christ in 1992. Over the years, the agency has had a considerable impact on the lives of economically disadvantaged and minority families who may otherwise feel threatened by larger public agencies. Initially created in response to a critical shortage of African American foster homes, the Family Enrichment Center provides the community with a family-centered, friendly, compassionate, neighborhood-based alternative to public and traditional social services.\n\nAs the only licensed minority-owned and operated child-placing agency in the southeastern United States, FEC provides care for approximately 250-350 children on a monthly basis. Through public-private partnerships, the agency has been able to maximize the utilization of limited resources, while maintaining high levels of professionalism and quality services.\n\nAn important mission of the agency is to be as responsive as possible to vulnerable children and families to ensure parents have the support they need to help provide their children with the quality of life they deserve. This is done through a variety of family-centered programs that address such critical issues as:\n\n    * Finding both substitute and permanent homes for children who have been removed from their families because of abuse and\/or neglect\n    * Provision of services to children and families affected by HIV\/AIDS\n    * Prevention of the breakdown of the family through early intervention and support",

	"Description": "For more than 80 years, United Way Suncoast has helped millions of deserving people and has been the charitable partner for hundreds of Bay Area agencies, businesses and civic organizations. During nearly nine decades of service, United Way has invested millions of dollars that directly and indirectly touch nearly every man, woman and child in Hillsborough, DeSoto, Sarasota and Pinellas Counties.\nUnited Way Suncoast is focusing on a community impact agenda that works to enhance the building blocks for a good life. The framework for this agenda are the Four Cornerstones of Caring:\n\n\u2022 Caring to Help Children & Youth Achieve Their Potential\n     Goal: cut in half the number of young people who dropout of high school.\n\n\u2022 Caring to Assist Individuals & Families to Achieve Financial Stability\n     Goal: cut in half the number of lower-income families that lack financial stability\n\n\u2022 Caring to Create Vibrant Neighborhoods\n     Goal: increase by one third the number of youths and adults who are healthy\n     and avoid risky behaviors\n\n\u2022 Caring to Support a Safety Net of Services\n    Goal: ensure emergency services to assist individuals and families in crisis.\n\nUnited Way leadership both facilitates and coordinates with regional agencies to fund programs that support these four areas of impact. 	"Description": "The Hillsborough HEART Program is a Department of Housing and Urban Development funded program managed by Agency for Community Treatment Services, Inc. (herein referred to as ACTS).  The program will serve 100 adult individuals using a housing first model to provide housing for each participant.  Persons eligible for services are persons meeting the HUD definition of chronically homeless and who, as a result of disabling conditions, are identified by the Tampa Hillsborough Homeless Initiative as the highest priority for placement in permanent, supportive housing. HUD is also funding ACTS to provide the tenants with comprehensive community services needed to assist with their disabilities and to provide sufficient support to enable them to successfully maintain housing.  Program staff will be on call 24\/7 to the tenant and landlord to assist with any emergent needs. \n\nIn preparation for the start up of the Program ACTS is soliciting landlords interested in entering into extended lease agreements. Specifically, ACTS is seeking to identify 100 housing units (Efficiencies, SRO's and 1 and 2 Bedroom Apartments) dispersed across Hillsborough County, The leases for the units will be directly between ACTS and the landlord, with ACTS entering into subleases with the tenants. Participating landlords will be compensated fair market value, inclusive of utilities. Landlords can expect no disruption in lease payments due to vacancies as it will be incumbent on ACTS to keep the units full at all times. ACTS' will maintain insurance to cover property damage.  Landlords must be amenable to regular code enforcement inspections.",

	"Description": "SSVF provides supportive services to extremely low-income veterans and their families residing in or transitioning to permanent housing in Pinellas, Pasco, and Hillsborough Counties.  We do this through a variety of services including case management, housing counseling, assistance in obtaining VA and public benefits, and temporary financial assistance.  We assist homeless veterans (individuals and families), as well as veterans who are at imminent-risk of becoming homeless, whether they are facing eviction, staying with friends or family and have to leave, or staying in a motel they can no longer pay for.  Temporary financial assistance must assist the individual\/family in accessing or maintaining housing.  If individual or family is not expecting a housing crisis, they are not eligible for assistance through SSVF.  Financial assistance that is provided includes security\/utility deposit, rental and utility assistance, moving\/storage costs, child care, transportation (bus passes) and possible motel assistance. 	"Description": "SSVF provides supportive services to extremely low-income veterans and their families residing in or transitioning to permanent housing in Pinellas, Pasco and Hillsborough Counties.  We do this through a variety of services including case management, housing counseling, assistance in obtaining VA and public benefits, and temporary financial assistance.  We assist homeless veterans (individuals and families), as well as veterans who are at imminent-risk of becoming homeless, whether they are facing eviction, staying with friends or family and have to leave, or staying in a motel they can no longer pay for.  Temporary financial assistance must assist the individual\/family in accessing or maintaining housing.  If individual or family is not experiencing a housing crisis, they are not eligible for assistance through SSVF.  Financial assistance that is provided includes security\/utility deposit, rental and utility assistance, moving\/storage costs, child care, transportation (bus passes), and possible motel assistance.  Again, the households served through this program MUST BE experiencing a housing crisis in order to be eligible for services through SSVF.",

We assist homeless veterans (individuals and families) as well as veterans who are at imminent-risk of becoming homeless, whether they are facing eviction, staying with friends or family and they have to leave, or staying in a motel they can no longer pay for. 	"IntakeProcedure": "The waitlist for Section 8 rental assistance was opened late October 2006 and over 10,000 families applied.  All families were placed on the applicant list based on a lottery system, and then are pulled from the list by local preferences. Those preferences are working, going to school, rent burdened, homeless, disabled, or living in substandard conditions.\n\nIt is important that if there is a new mailing address, that it is reported to the office in person or in writing. Providing information over the phone will not be accepted, because this type of effort can not be tracked.\n\nThe agency does not offer any type of emergency assistance. All families will be assisted from the waitlist by order of the lottery and preferences.  \n\nThe agency will not be able to predict when any applicant will receive assistance. The agency only has 5,209 vouchers to assist all of Hillsborough County. Therefore, in order to assist someone from the waitlist, someone must leave the Section 8 rental assistance program. We do however remove at least 50 families a month or 700 families a year from the Section 8 rental assistance program, and then pull that same amount from the waitlist.  Example: your number on the waitlist is 1,000, and if the agency assists 700 from the list, your position on the list should move up to 300. This may fluctuate due to some families may have a local preference and will be placed back on the list. When a family is called in to determine their eligibility, we also have to determine and ensure that family meets the preference and if that family can not prove their preference, they then go back on the list. So if your number was 25 at one point, and then we placed somebody back on the list, it may go to 26.\n\nWhen your name comes to the top of the list, you will be sent a written notification to either provide information or a notice of an appointment. You must attend the appointment or provide information in order to be considered for rental assistance. If 2 notices are sent without a response, your name will automatically be removed from the waitlist.\n\nYou will have the right to an informal review, but it must be sent in writing within 10 days of THA sending the notice to remove from the waitlist.",

	"Description": "ATHENA House:  Female Veteran Transitional Housing Program\n\nPROGRAM DESCRIPTION:  \nThe ATHENA House is a safe, secure, drug and alcohol free (DRY) housing with 24 hour supervision by support staff.  It is a 16-bed facility designed to provide safe and stable housing to homeless female veterans who are eligible for this service-related benefit.  ATHENA offers up to 24-months of housing with a focus on increasing income so that they may re-enter the community in an independent setting.  We also provide assistance to access entitlements, employment, health care, counseling, transportation, and basic needs.  The program is staffed 24\/7\/365.  The ATHENA House works closely with the James A. Haley and Bay Pines VA Hospitals in coordinating access to this program as well as other veteran serving organizations.  The ATHENA House also works closely with Tampa Crossroads' Veterans Assistance Center to help clients achieve employment and housing goals.  This Grant per diem program is the first in Florida to offer gender sensitive housing for female veterans.\n\nDESCRIPTION OF SERVICES:\nThe primary goal of the ATHENA House is to assist the clients become stable, independent, productive, and healthy members of their community.  Clients may receive counseling and case management to address their substance abuse problems and\/or their mental illness, to learn the life skills necessary to function independently, to address educational goals, and to find and retain full time employment or access entitled government benefits needed to support permanent independent living.  Individual and group counseling sessions are available to all clients.\n\nThis is a 24 month GPD Program.  Must be a female veteran approved for housing benefits by V.A.  Must be a homeless female veteran qualified for V.A. housing benefits.  Stay up to 24 months.  Resident must pay 30% max income.\n\nThe Grant Per Diem (GPD) program offers supportive housing (up to 24 months) to homeless Veterans with substance use, mental illness or dual diagnosis problems.  There are 3 agencies where beds are located which include ACTS, Volunteers of America and Tampa Crossroads.  Each agency has their own entry requirements and processing.",

A Veteran is defined as having served at least 1 day of active duty with an above dishonorable discharge.  A DD214 or VA letter is required for eligibility determination and documentation.\n\n2.  Very Low-Income: Household income does not exceed 50% of Area Median Income (AMI).  Documentation of income is required for eligibility determination.\n\n3.  Occupying Permanent Housing:  Either (a) are residing in permanent housing; (b) are homeless and scheduled to become a resident of permanent housing within 90 days pending the location or development of housing suitable for permanent housing; or, (c) have exited permanent housing within the previous 90 days to seek other housing that is responsive to the needs and preferences of the household.\n\n**A Pre-Screening can be done over the phone to determine basic eligibility.",

	"Description": "OUR VISION:  Our vision is to be leaders in creating partnerships and bringing resources into the community.  Our efforts recognize and use assessment, planning , rehabilitation, and accountability as the most desirable alternatives to help our clients move toward independence and family stability.  \n\nOUR MISSION:  Providing holistic, client-centered, family-focused opportunities for positive change and personal accountability through evidence-based treatment, housing, and supportive services.\n\nOUR HISTORY:  Tampa Crossroads, Inc. was established by Sister Rose Christina Momm in 1977 as a halfway house for men being released from prison.  Since that time, the agency has grown from its original one facility traditional halfway house to the extensive service continuum that it offers today.  Referrals are accepted from the courts, probation officers, case managers, Veteran Administration, Public Defenders office, Department of Corrections, jail and prison staff, and individual self-referral.  Tampa Crossroads, Inc. accepts individuals, who are motivated to make positive changes in their lives, remain drug and alcohol free, abide by and remain compliant with program rules and principles.\n\nOUR TREATMENT PHILOSOPHY:  Our treatment philosophy includes acknowledging that each of our clients is unique regardless of their background or referral source and therefore the individual needs, motivation, strengths, and challenges must be identified in each client.  Rather than addressing only the presenting problem such as mental illness, substance abuse, trauma, joblessness, or homelessness, we work with our clients to create a plan that will address all of their needs.  Approaches used in addressing clients' needs include those found in Choice Theory and SMART Recovery.",

	"Description": "Supportive Services for Veteran Families (SSVF) Program\n\nThe SSVF Program is funded by the VA and was awarded to the Homeless Coalition of Hillsborough County in partnership with Tampa Crossroads, Inc. in October of 2011.  Through the SSVF Program, the VA aims to improve very low-income Veteran families' housing stability through the provision of outreach and case management services and will assist participants to obtain VA benefits and other public benefits, which may include:\n\nHealth Care Services\nDaily Living Expenses\nPersonal Financial Planning Services \nTransportation Services\nFiduciary and Payee Services\nLegal Services \nChild Care Services \nHousing Counseling Services\nTemporary Financial Assistance - including time-limited payments to third parties for rent, utilities, moving expenses, security and utility deposits, transportation, child care and emergency supplies.\n\nAll direct services for the SSVF Program are coordinated out of our Veterans Assistance Center, which also offers services to veterans and their families under the VHPD and F-HVRP programs (for more info see program descriptions).  The Center is close to public transportation routes and the location in Hillsborough County leverages other community partners to assist this hard to place population with finding sustainable employment and housing in order to achieve stability and independence.",
	"ChangeDescription": "",
	"DirectServiceCode": "Yes",
	"Eligibility": "The basic eligibility requirements for the SSVF program according to VA guidelines are as follows:\n\n1.  Member of a Veteran Family:  A Veteran family is defined as a single person or a family in which the head of household or the spouse of the head of household is a Veteran.  A Veteran is defined as having served at least 1 day of active duty with an above dishonorable discharge.  A DD214 or VA letter is required for eligibility determination and documentation.\n\n2.  Very Low-Income: Household income does not exceed 50% of Area Median Income (AMI).  Documentation of income is required for eligibility determination.\n\n3.  Occupying Permanent Housing:  Either (a) are residing in permanent housing; (b) are homeless and scheduled to become a resident of permanent housing within 90 days pending the location or development of housing suitable for permanent housing; or, (c) have exited permanent housing within the previous 90 days to seek other housing that is responsive to the needs and peferences of the household.\n\n**A Pre-Screening can be done over the phone to determine basic eligibility.",

Through the SSVF Program, the VA aims to improve very low-income Veteran families' housing stability through the provision of outreach and case management services and will assist participants to obtain VA benefits and other public benefits, which may include:\n\nHealth Care Services\nDaily Living Expenses\nPersonal Financial Planning Services \nTransportation Services\nFiduciary and Payee Services\nLegal Services \nChild Care Services \nHousing Counseling Services\nTemporary Financial Assistance - including time-limited payments to third parties for rent, utilities, moving expenses, security and utility deposits, transportation, child care and emergency supplies.\n\nAll direct services for the SSVF Program are coordinated out of our Veterans Assistance Center, which also offers services to veterans and their families under the VHPD and F-HVRP programs (for more info see program descriptions).  The Center is close to public transportation routes and the location in Hillsborough County leverages other community partners to assist this hard to place population with finding sustainable employment and housing in order to achieve stability and independence.",

	"Eligibility": "The basic eligibility requirements for the SSVF program according to VA guidelines are as follows:\n\n1.  Member of a Veteran Family:  A Veteran family is defined as a single person or a family in which the head of household or the spouse of the head of household is a Veteran.  A Veteran is defined as having served at least 1 day of active duty with an above dishonorable discharge.  A DD214 or VA letter is required for eligibility determination and documentation.\n\n2.  Very Low-Income: Household income does not exceed 50% of Area Median Income (AMI).  Documentation of income is required for eligibility determination.\n\n3.  Occupying Permanent Housing:  Either (a) are residing in permanent housing; (b) are homeless and scheduled to become a resident of permanent housing within 90 days pending the location or development of housing suitable for permanent housing; or, (c) have exited permanent housing within the previous 90 days to seek other housing that is responsive to the needs and peferences of the household.\n\n**A Pre-Screening can be done over the phone to determine basic eligibility.",

	"Description": "WOMEN'S RESIDENTIAL PROGRAM - ROSE MANOR\n\nRose Manor residential program is a Level II Residential  Program licensed by the Florida Department of Children and Families for adult women who have been court-ordered or have a criminal history who are in need of services to assist them in returning to independence through employment and stability.  Clients may be referred for mental health and\/or substance abuse treatment.  The program is located in Hillsborough County and has the capacity to serve up to 18 residential clients.  Rose Manor offers an intensive treatment component, approximately 2 months in duration and a 4 month job skills\/re-entry component when the resident will be engaged in wage earning employment in the community.  The program is staffed 24\/7\/365.\n\nThe length of stay is on average 6 months of residential treatment while residing in the residential program and aftercare is recommended when the client has moved into independent living.\n\nDESCRIPTION OF SERVICES:\nRose Manor provides 24-hour residential supervision, individual and group counseling, supervision of medication, transportation, structured activity programs, and a varied education curriculum.  The education curriculum includes life skills education such as budgeting, communication, domestic skills, employability, problem-solving, and leisure skills, community awareness, opportunities for leisure activities, access to community resources, and awareness of available social services and, substance abuse education and treatment, on topics such as drug interaction and relapse prevention.  A variety of evidence-based practices are used in group and individual counseling.  Clients are referred to other agencies for identified needed services beyond the scope of services provided by this program.\n\nWhile clients are in the program, family members are encouraged to participate.  Counseling and family education groups are available to assist clients and family members in becoming better educated about what the clients are learning.  This is a confidential program and NO INFORMATION is given out without a signed ROI in place.",

	"Description": "VETERANS HOMELESSNESS PREVENTION DEMONSTRATION PROJECT (VHPD)\n\nThe Veterans Homelessness Prevention Demonstration Project (VHPD) is a new initiative by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), the U.S. Department of Veterans' Affairs (VA), and the U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) to provide assistance to veterans at-risk of becoming homeless or newly homeless.  \n\nThe Tampa\/Hillsborough County Homeless Continuum of Care (led by the Homeless Coalition of Hillsborough County) was selected as one of 5communities in the country for this program to help veterans in the 4 counties served by the James A. Haley VA Hospital including Hillsborough, Pasco, Polk, and Hernando.  Tampa Crossroads, Inc. is a partner agency providing direct services out of our Veterans Assistance Center for participants in Hillsborough County.\n\nThe VHPD project's target population is:  \n\n* Veterans returning from Iraq (OIF) and Afghanistan (OEF)\n* Female veterans\n* Veterans with families especially with a single head of household\n* National Guard and Reserve\n\nTo be considered at-risk of becoming homeless, the household must have at least 1 of the following Housing Instability Criteria listed below:\n\n* At least one month (30  days) behind in rent\n* Eviction within 2 weeks from a private dwelling (including housing provided by friends and family\n* Discharge within 2 weeks from an institution in which the person has been a resident for more than 180 days (prisons, mental health institutions, hospitals)\n* Residency in housing that has been condemned by housing officials and is no longer meant for human habitation\n* At least one month (30 days) behind in utilties\n* Housing cost burdened (greater than 50 percent of income spent on housing costs)\n* Sudden and significant loss of income (>25 percent) such as\n* Recent institutional care\n* Recent traumatic life event (divorce, death of spouse\/primary care giver, recent health crisis that prevented household from meeting financial responsibilities)\n* Imminent unemployment (due to mass layoffs at work site, movement of company, unstable employment, underemployment)\n* Mental health and substance abuse\n\nHomeless veterans who have been homeless for less than 90 days are also eligible (if meets all criteria).",

	"Description": "OUTPATIENT SERVICES\n\nTampa Crossroads, Inc. Non-Residential Services is licensed by the Florida Department of Children and Families to provide outpatient treatment and aftercare counseling.  Clients may be referred for mental health, anger management, and\/or substance abuse treatment.  Clients may also be referred for drug and alcohol testing.  The program is located in Hillsborough County.  \n\nNon-Residential Services provides outpatient treatment, case management, drug and alcohol evaluations, aftercare services, and drug and alcohol testing.  It is designed to provide treatment services to adults who are in need of co-occurring treatment services and do not require a residential setting.  Treatment at this program consists of individual and group sessions.  These sessions address topics related to substance abuse, mental health, anger management, coping skills, self-esteem, communication, problem solving, time management, and awareness of community resources.  A variety of evidence-based practices are used in group and individual counseling.  Clients are referred to other agencies for identified needed services beyond the scope of services provided by this program.",

	"Description": "Female and Families Homeless Veterans Reintegration Program (F-HVRP)\n\nTampa Crossroads, Inc. opened the Veterans Employment Network (VEN) in 2009 using DOL funding awarded under the F-HVRP grant.  The primary goal of the program is to provide job skills training and employment services to homeless female veterans or male veterans with minor children, as well as single homeless female veterans.  The program focuses on housing stability, job readiness and career counseling, short-term job skills trainings and certifications\/licenses, and job search and placement support.  Follow-up services are provided for 270 days beginning with the first day of employment in order to ensure successful job retention.  \n\nThis program is operated out of our Veterans Assistance Center, which also provides direct services to veterans and their families under the VHPD and SSVF programs (for more info see program descriptions) including housing assistance and supportive services. 	"Description": "VETERANS HOMELESSNESS PREVENTION DEMONSTRATION PROJECT (VHPD)\n\nThe Veterans Homelessness Prevention Demonstration Project (VHPD) is a new initiative by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), the U.S. Department of Veterans' Affairs (VA), and the U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) to provide assistance to veterans at-risk of becoming homeless or newly homeless.  \n\nThe Tampa\/Hillsborough County Homeless Continuum of Care (led by the Homeless Coalition of Hillsborough County) was selected as one of 5communities in the country for this program to help veterans in the 4 counties served by the James A. Haley VA Hospital including Hillsborough, Pasco, Polk, and Hernando.  Tampa Crossroads, Inc. is a partner agency providing direct services out of our Veterans Assistance Center for participants in Hillsborough County.\n\nThe VHPD project's target population is:  \n\n* Veterans returning from Iraq (OIF) and Afghanistan (OEF)\n* Female veterans\n* Veterans with families especially with a single head of household\n* National Guard and Reserve\n\nTo be considered at-risk of becoming homeless, the household must have at least 1 of the following Housing Instability Criteria listed below:\n\n* At least one month (30  days) behind in rent\n* Eviction within 2 weeks from a private dwelling (including housing provided by friends and family\n* Discharge within 2 weeks from an institution in which the person has been a resident for more than 180 days (prisons, mental health institutions, hospitals)\n* Residency in housing that has been condemned by housing officials and is no longer meant for human habitation\n* At least one month (30 days) behind in utilties\n* Housing cost burdened (greater than 50 percent of income spent on housing costs)\n* Sudden and significant loss of income (>25 percent) such as\n* Recent institutional care\n* Recent traumatic life event (divorce, death of spouse\/primary care giver, recent health crisis that prevented household from meeting financial responsibilities)\n* Imminent unemployment (due to mass layoffs at work site, movement of company, unstable employment, underemployment)\n* Mental health and substance abuse\n\nHomeless veterans who have been homeless for less than 90 days are also eligible (if meets all criteria).",

	"Description": "Treatment services are individualized, with different types and intensities of treatment approaches, according to the specific needs, strengths, abilities, and preferences of the person served.  Group and individual therapy sessions are provided throughout the treatment stay.  Educational groups are provided daily to address health and safety, recreation, living skills, finances, relationships, family systems, decision-making skills, nutrition, etc.  Random urine screenings are conducted.  Comprehensive case management services are provided while in treatment.  Transportation services are made available.  Room, board and supervision are provided.  Employment readiness services are provided.  All persons served will be introduced to the 12 step program and philosophy model.  \n\nThe Grant Per Diem (GPD) program offers supportive housing (up to 24 months) to homeless Veterans with substance use, mental illness, or dual diagnosis problems.  There are 3 agencies where beds are located which include ACTS, Volunteers of America, and Tampa Crossroads.  Each agency has their own entry requirements and processing.",

Member of a Veteran Family:  A Veteran family is defined as a single person or a family in which the head of household or the spouse of the head of household is a Veteran.  A Veteran is defined as having served at least 1 day of active duty with an above dishonorable discharge.  A DD214 or VA letter is required for eligibility determination and documentation.\n\n2.  Very Low-Income: Household income does not exceed 50% of Area Median Income (AMI).  Documentation of income is required for eligibility determination.\n\n3.  Occupying Permanent Housing:  Either (a) are residing in permanent housing; (b) are homeless and scheduled to become a resident of permanent housing within 90 days pending the location or development of housing suitable for permanent housing; or, (c) have exited permanent housing within the previous 90 days to seek other housing that is responsive to the needs and preferences of the household.\n\n**A Pre-Screening can be done over the phone to determine basic eligibility.",

Our efforts recognize and use assessment, planning , rehabilitation, and accountability as the most desirable alternatives to help our clients move toward independence and family stability.  \n\nOUR MISSION:  Providing holistic, client-centered, family-focused opportunities for positive change and personal accountability through evidence-based treatment, housing, and supportive services.\n\nOUR HISTORY:  Tampa Crossroads, Inc. was established by Sister Rose Christina Momm in 1977 as a halfway house for men being released from prison.  Since that time, the agency has grown from its original one facility traditional halfway house to the extensive service continuum that it offers today.  Referrals are accepted from the courts, probation officers, case managers, Veteran Administration, Public Defenders office, Department of Corrections, jail and prison staff, and individual self-referral.  Tampa Crossroads, Inc. accepts individuals, who are motivated to make positive changes in their lives, remain drug and alcohol free, abide by and remain compliant with program rules and principles.\n\nOUR TREATMENT PHILOSOPHY:  Our treatment philosophy includes acknowledging that each of our clients is unique regardless of their background or referral source and therefore the individual needs, motivation, strengths, and challenges must be identified in each client.  Rather than addressing only the presenting problem such as mental illness, substance abuse, trauma, joblessness, or homelessness, we work with our clients to create a plan that will address all of their needs.
